Barack Obama will be the fourth U.S. president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth U.S. president in history.
The diploma, medal and check of $1.4 million will be awarded, among other things, for the exceptional effort in strengthening global diplomacy and cooperation between nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have plenty to do.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he meets the five members of the committee that, in October, chose him from 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with the Norwegian king, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
It will be the fourth U.S. president to receive him, although the third to receive him in his office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will talk about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and cheque of ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kronor).
It is proposed to donate them to charitable paraffins, but it has not yet decided to which organization in particular.
During their full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet attended by the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama had a rather reserved attitude towards the award from the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling that he did not deserve it at all.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for everyone who fights for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents “a challenge to take action.”
