USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It’s funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats on the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the foolishest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it proved to be a copy of the script Bush used for Iraq, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "the same as in Iraq" repeatedly used in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward."
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country suffering from the civil war, and criticized it as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, proved that Bush’s strategy, based on recommendations from field captains, was the only one possible and successful, so that today nothing is said about Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, however objectively he left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan Operation General Stanley McCristal, who, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided rifles in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he deceived the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finishing this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only one people of Potemkin, and patriarchal tribal relations will remain behind him.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confused relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “capable of action,” a minimum target of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy collides with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon" will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans have less and less willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem by military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years to go before the presidential election, so there is still a lot of time to come up with another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
