The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some already accessible drugs.
AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, patients’ lives can be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarboranes have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way unlike all medicines used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘enhanced’ compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus’s albumin.
Metallocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are bonded by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitorous and resilient virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, HIV virus fractionation does not occur and mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would not be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, explain the scientists in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was carried out on a specimen, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of metallocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in the clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on the resistant variants, in which the drugs often do not work.
The mechanism of the unique effect, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications, makes metallocarborans interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína <0xC5><0x98>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová, head of the laboratory of structural biology at the Institute of organic and biochemical chemistry and the Institute of Molecular Chemistry.
