On the other hand, the Defense Minister, whose party is associated with the UMP, planned to confirm the strategy on Saturday before the NC National Council.
In support of its management, he received the help of the deputy Hervé de Charette (former UMP, now NC) who claimed ownership of the UDF brand, as he was the first to register it with the National Institute of Industrial Property in 2004.
But on Friday night, the office of the UDF association, controlled by Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou’s friends who do not want to be deprived of it, broke the silence to issue a request to the Minister and the deputy urging them to renounce the acronym and transfer the rights of ownership of the trademark to them, under penalty of judicial demand.
In recent days, you have made many statements implying that you would propose to your political movement to recover the acronym UDF, writes the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the office, including Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Athuis of the Central Alliance.
They also believe it right to continue the use of the movement’s name, the +Nouveau centre+, and the slogan +UDF d’aujourd’hui+ in their militant material and on the presentation page of their site, the signatories of the letter argue.
As you already know, they have no right to use the acronym, explains the UDF office that demands that the NC remove "immediately the mention of the name of the UDF from any support, as well as from (its) Internet site."
It also asks Hervé de Charette "to transfer ownership of the trademark to the legitimate holders."
Failure to do so will result in an appeal to the courts to uphold the law and the legitimate rights of the members of the UDF, the signatories warn.
In the letter, they specify that the UDF "is a real political movement since 1978" and recall that Morin and his friends "elected" to leave in 2007 "to create a new party, as others had already done in 2002 to create the UMP".
Accordingly, the New Center has no right to use the acronym UDF.
They also recall that the last congress of the UDF in 2007 voted to join the MoDem for three years and the creation of an office in charge of defending "the material and moral interests" of the movement founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the office continues, "when he registered the trademark", he was no longer "member of the UDF for three years", but of the UMP.
It uses the absence of registration of the acronym UDF scandalously and fraudulently to carry out it on its own.
This indiscretion is turning into a crime, they denounce, before mocking the strategy of the NC: "We believe that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make its own name than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which one is not entitled."
Liliane Bettencourt case: Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois-Marie Banier will be tried for abuse of weakness
On Friday, the court in Nanterre decided to bring artist Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois-Marie Banier to trial to determine whether, as the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt claims, she took advantage of the eighty-year-old’s state of weakness to plunder her part of her fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photographs of the stars of the show, will be tried on 15 and 16 April 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime whose conviction consists of a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This means that in this case there will be a saga-worthy process about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter dispute the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetic empire.
But Correctional Court No. 15 also ordered 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt to undergo a medical examination by three medical professionals.
The heir and main shareholder of L'Oréal always refused to undergo such examinations, even more so under the conditions proposed by the Prosecutor's Office of Nanterre during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday must submit a report by March 10, 2010, stating whether and during which periods Liliane Bettencourt suffered from weakness.
I think he will.
I’m going to talk to her,” said Mrs. Bettencourt’s lawyer, Georges Kiesman, as he left the hearing.
For his part, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise Bettencourt-Meyers’ lawyer, Olivier Metzner, was pleased with the court’s decision.
“The investigation will show that he (Banier) manipulated this older lady, whom we must protect,” he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt’s only daughter has filed criminal lawsuits against Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois-Marie Banier, a multifaceted photographer and artist, accusing him of years of taking advantage of her mother’s weakness to obtain a billion euros in donations, through cheques, life insurance contracts or artwork.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied being manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-standing friend.
On Friday, while the court was examining the provenance of the action brought by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers’ allegations were, on some occasions, a great family confession.
In this way, Liliane Bettencourt’s lawyer took into account three letters that her client sent (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary in which she said she was suspicious of Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise Bettencourt-Meyers’ husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "I could explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once or twice a day for fifteen years.
Since her wedding, I have never been able to talk to Fran<0xC3><0xA7>oise again.”
For its part, the Prosecutor’s Office of Nanterre once again considered that the plaintiff was unable to appear, all the more so as a guardianship judge has refused, in recent days, to give rise to her request to open a judicial guardianship procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to appear before the courts, is not under guardianship and has no guardian.
No other person will be able to appear in his place," prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney said.
Finally, the court decided that it would rule on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers once the trial had taken place.
Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees reminds of the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as it used to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to the strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
Demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more so, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) “requires that all parties involved ... have a proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision”; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that completely opposes the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we call for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the concerns of the company as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the Orange questionnaire among its employees, incite managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all the companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behaviorist theory that the American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos investigation published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management stance, unsuited to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating into every business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is possible only if it clearly appears as a means to make a part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Nowadays, only studies from Motif Functional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “in place”.
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo speech: for ‘just war’ Obama receives praise from the right
On Friday, the U.S. right-wing, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize defended the concept of “just war” against U.S. enemies, hailed the speech that Obama had delivered on Thursday.
The Conservatives, who had discredited the award to Obama on Oct. 9, this time applauded the presidential address, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, said Mrs. Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican party to USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of “sometimes necessary” war in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
We have to stop the terrorists, he said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, devoted himself Thursday in Oslo to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another Obama adversary, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really great, the former Speaker of the House was pleased, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
At times, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, whom some view as a potential Republican inauguration candidate for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear from "a left-wing president" when he reminded Nobel Committee members "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush’s speeches and current Washington Post chronicler, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a “citizen of the world,” as “he always does,” he “talked as an American president” by reminding Europeans “that they live in a security bubble that they didn’t create and that they don’t do much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the unconvinced few on the right, a Bush-era hawk, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, called the speech “monotonous, pretentious and uninspired” on the National Review Online website.
On the left of the president, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover the war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, while still believing that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech “overproduction” especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech “should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression,” the California newspaper said enthusiastically.
Obama “made the speech that was necessary,” the New York Times said, judging it “both gloomy and uplifting.”
Road transport: three marathon negotiations to ensure Christmas supply
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the road trade unions and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employers' organization that remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday afternoon that ends the slogan of strike and the threat that rests on Christmas supply.
During the signing session on Friday night, Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "joyed" by the deal, following several negotiating sessions that began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators said goodbye at dawn on Friday in hopes of quickly signing the text according to late in the morning.
Even when three employers’ organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew by knocking the door.
But a meeting of more than six hours that began at 11 a.m. was necessary for all to agree and the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict “had been very damaging to businesses” and “they were afraid it would disrupt the holidays at the end of the year,” Bussereau said.
The text envisages an increase of 4 per cent for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and 2.9 per cent for the highest wages (international transport).
The hourly rate rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 for low wages.
It’s not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
If so, we will give orders to our militants that there will be no more cuts or blockages in the sourcing centers.
But there can always be some disconforming rebels, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that this is "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases to high wages given international competition".
According to him, the increases will be in the order of 170 euros per month for the low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is a common-sense agreement that respects employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognized it as “a historic agreement.”
For Richard Jaubert (CGT) it is “an acceptable compromise.”
The agreement also envisages an increase in travel costs of 3% and the holding of general assemblies of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will allow to address above all the issue of an extraordinary payment and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that "a 100 million euro drop in employers' burdens" was the subject of an amendment by the government in the 2009 rectification finance bill, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote “on the same terms.”
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to apply, firstly, to the companies that are members of this organization and, secondly, to the whole profession, in the event that the Minister of Labour makes an extension.
It will be done “as soon as possible,” Bussereau said.
The opposition of employers’ organisations could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced that it was a "business of naives", since the 100 million euros "had already been pledged to the sector to compensate for part of the CO2 tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but to not counter those who wish to eat turkey at the next Christmas Eve dinner, lamented Unostra.
The agreement puts the stability of many SMEs in the sector at risk over the next 12 months.
