Turkish Justice Dissolves Prokurd Party, A Decision With Serious Consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled on Friday in favor of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately sparked anger in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the government’s task, which has just extended a hand to the Kurdish community trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The party of the Democratic Society (DTP) was disbanded because it had become "the focus of activities that damaged the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the Court, Hasim Kili<0xC3><0xA7>, told the press after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a majority of seven votes was needed to obtain the dissolution, Kili<0xC3><0xA7> said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and lawmaker Aysel Tugluk, are removed from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the cessation of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party’s assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 benches in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that deputies would leave parliament before becoming parliamentarians without a partisan label.
The ruling follows a procedure launched by Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yal<0xC3><0xA7>inkaya in 2007, accusing the DTP of obeying the “principles” of the Kurdistan Workers’ Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Numerous observers believe the DTP is the legal political showcase of PKK rebels.
However, the party says it has no "organic links" with the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government reaches out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights, so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and thus end the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to heightened tensions in the Southeast Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the conditions of detention of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan have degenerated into clashes with police over the past few weeks.
Since the proclamation of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP’s premises in Diyarbakir, the large town of the Southeast mostly populated by Kurds.
The Order Forces threw tear grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov bombs or sling stones.
In Istanbul, about one hundred people were also concentrated.
Following the verdict, Türk said the court’s decision would “deep down the discouragement.”
Turkey cannot resolve this issue (Kurdish, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
In principle, we oppose the closure of parties.
Nothing is resolved in this way, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack in which seven soldiers were killed three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
The snow can start suddenly
A truly cool winter is what Wolfgang Brauburger desires.
It’s not at all something that you want to make life impossible for citizens, says the FES Winter Road Maintenance Director
But with this, your employees can learn to test and master the entirety of vehicle technology.
On the weekend, meteorologists may announce it for the first time.
More than 330 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of snow and ice.
In this case, the FES acts in accordance with a thorough plan.
As soon as it snows heavily in Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero degrees, 20 of the so-called A-strips come out with large salted vehicles, Brauburger explains.
These include, for example, the main arteries and avenues such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
But also the accesses for the firefighters, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping sections, such as the Atzelbergstraße.
The FES service starts around three in the morning
They should cover approximately 1,040 kilometers, as needed, in a maximum of three hours with wet salt, which adheres better.
That’s why the FES starts around three o’clock in the morning, “with this the tracks are free until rush hour traffic begins”.
The hard part is when it starts to snow around 7:30 am.
"Then we have a problem," says the director of road maintenance in winter, "because then no one is ready to clear space for vehicles with salt."
Immediately afterwards, when it is no longer snowing, it is up to the secondary and private roads, to which also belongs the Rat-Beil-Straße.
The last priority is the side and secondary streets.
That's where the inconveniences are generated, Brauburger tastes good.
Around five o’clock in the morning the FES infantry sets off, mainly the hazardous points and cruisers are cleared.
Usually the FES could not take over the entirety of the bike lanes.
In Frankfurt there is a special service, which from 10 p.m. to 4:30 p.m. does not lose sight of mainly the bridges, says Brauburger.
As these become slippery quickly, the salted vehicle starts as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
In case of an emergency, the police can also call them.
The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa found looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high running on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of millions of years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa find was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triasic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the sauriers were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadrupedal sauropods known as the "long neck", and their relatives, and the Ornithisch aherbis.
According to the analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa’s skull, researchers found indications of air bags, such as those owned by descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to airbags, birds’ breathing is more efficient than mammals’.
In the case of Tawa, the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related lineage of later giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Accordingly, the three genealogical lineages were separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa found the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
All three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the study Science.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs expanded around the world and many new species developed, while kinship was extinct on the Triassic boundary towards the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It could have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and international signatories.
