New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret armament investigation.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Important research and production centres for micro and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted the Riedberg scientific headquarters in Frankfurt, the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
Several mutual visits were made and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign a "Protocol of Close Collaboration" in Frankfurt.
Moscow Deputy Mayor Juri Rosljak and the Mayor of Selengrad, Anatoly Smirnov, led the Russian delegation; for Frankfurt, the head of planning services Edwin Schwarz signed.
In 2010, representatives of FIZ and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises from the natural sciences research centre will travel to a seminar in Selenograd.
