Dream worlds
In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only in the case of mentally ill and drug addicts, the boundaries between imagination and reality fade.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can give ourselves unfettered to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, whoever experiences sleep-like states during waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often regarded in the modern Western world as a madman or drug addict, or at least as a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes blur the boundaries between dream, madness and reality.
The dream-modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, insanity.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Casta<0xC3><0xB1>eda, the states of shamanic possession, and the psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts often appear.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between insanity and dream has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a wakeful state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness to the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, this dream was even "a psychosis, with all the misappropriate, misappropriate forms".
It is the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over it, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with blood-red faces, deformed, grinding their teeth.
They are chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Crying, malignant voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls out two stereo cables, ties them to form a hanging knot, and fixes them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a horn and puts the knot around the neck.
Jump. Jump.
The rope is loosened.
What a lesson for you!, the voices shout in a choir that blows his eardrums, "Go to the clinic and make you heal!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, in addition to being manic-depressive, he takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality.
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the lifetime of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most frequent disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, grandeur delusions, relationship disorders, or persecutive mania.
Especially widespread is the hearing of voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like dream, psychosis also opens the gates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning aimed at it.
At the same time he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, awakening, impossible.
Have experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, “the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is.”
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers it is still unclear why our brain makes cabriolets.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can lead anyone to lose contact with reality provisionally.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes, there are also other determinants.
The researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the trigger of a psychosis when a pre-disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitter system.
When the brain heats up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive medications to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experiment with some, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been compiling reports on hallucinations and visions for the past ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreal Welt in unserem Kopf, published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with psychic disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and cranioencephal trauma.
Surprisingly, and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or poorly inhibited; when our brain warms up, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulus restriction, stress, love sickness or other brain states of exception.
In recent studies, up to one-third of respondents reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it weren't for those pictures and the voices.
Sometimes, during recess, it happens that a clumsy boy with long, dark hair speaks to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her astonished; no one, besides her, hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a little weird dreamer, but Sarah K. Knows she's not dreaming.
She wakes up and goes and hears that guy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the boy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class he can sometimes not follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is presenting a new companion, while for the rest he explains the mathematical equations in a visible and audible way.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the sleep to arrive, which often comes late and is scarce, she does not know whether she is awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the faces or the girl with bleeding cuts in her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
Her parents and friends haven't told her anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is today 20 years old.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago the hallucinations disappeared.
Since she’s contacted psychologist Kasten via the Internet, she knows she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of despair.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a stimulus restriction, it is very likely that after a while they will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is vacant and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., the only child, was little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he calls dad since he uses reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "has place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are equally images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.
Kasten also classifies night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate his hallucinations as a special skill.
The boundary between sleep and hallucination
In this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences usually pathologize, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a harsh and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called Oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that they cannot subsequently differentiate from being awake.
Dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully aware.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of himself or the world due to a total and permanent motor incapacity, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with an own and imaginary world that is detached from reality.
A form of borderline situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unendurable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his dreamlike experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on multi-day trips after a heart valve surgery with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he found himself lying in bed, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the early Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and encountered a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describes your experience.
On the contrary, memories of mental travel are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, the oneirism, psychoses, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Every change in the state of consciousness, psychologist Kasten summarizes, “can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.”
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
