75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Feducation and career path of women in Spain', developed by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of living together as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, start living together as a couple, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
By contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
“Women aged 35 to 49 with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after the beginning of cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time of their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity but less on the timing of pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when getting married and having the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the older the age at which they are married and at which they have the first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher studies were first mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 on average, respectively.
"There is also another division between women based on their level of education.
While those who have elementary studies get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those of middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and prioritize getting a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child.
