Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock brakes and will pass with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by its way of working, it can also help prevent many collisions by range.
The emergency braking assistant does what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the step that the driver gives.
But this does not always maintain that pressure until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to step on the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance that the car uses to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting lightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
